<DOC><DOCNO> AP901007-0078 </DOCNO><FILEID>AP-NY-10-07-90 2127EDT</FILEID><FIRST>r i AM-BRF--Germany-Rightist     10-07 0153</FIRST><SECOND>AM-BRF--Germany-Rightists,0151</SECOND><HEAD>Ultra-Rightist Party Holds First Meeting in Former East Germany</HEAD><DATELINE>ERFURT, Germany (AP) </DATELINE><TEXT>   The right-wing National Democratic Partyon Sunday held its first rally in the former territory of EastGermany and demanded that German borders be extended to theirpre-World War II limits.   The party, which is reported to have about 6,000 members informer West Germany, had been banned in Communist East Germany.   About 700 police officers in riot gear were deployed against anyclashes between the rightists and about 250 protesters, accordingto ADN, which before unification was the official East German newsagency. ADN did not say how many people attended the meeting.   Speakers said the unification of Germany last Wednesday shouldbe a first step toward the return of territory forfeited by Germansafter World War II, ADN reported. About one-third of present-dayPoland was German territory before the war.</TEXT></DOC>